implicitexplicit|Explicit and Implicit Information]])"}, {"ref": "to see", "text": "\"to observe\" or \"to look more closely\""}, {"ref": "one people with the same language", "text": "All the people were one big group and they all spoke the same language."}, {"ref": "nothing that they intend to do will be impossible for them", "text": "This double negative can also be translated as: \"anything they intend to do will be possible for them.\" It can also be translated as \"they will be able to do anything they want to do.\" (See: [[:en:ta:translate:double-negatives|Double Negatives]])"}, {"ref": "let us go down", "text": "The word \u201cus\u201d is plural even though it refers to God. Some translate it as \"let me go down\" or \u201cI will go down.\u201d If you do this, consider adding a footnote to say that the word is plural. (See the note on \"Let us make\" in [[:en:bible:notes:gen:01:26|1:26]].) ([[:en:ta:translate:pluralpronouns|English Plural Pronouns]])"}, {"ref": "confuse their language", "text": "This could also be translated \"mix up their language.\" This means that Yahweh would cause the people all over the earth to stop speaking the same language."}, {"ref": "so that the may not understand each other", "text": "This was the purpose of confusing their language. It can also be translated as \"so that they will not understand what each other is saying.\" (UDB)"}]}, {"id": "11-08", "tn": [{"ref": "from there", "text": "\"from the city\""}, {"ref": "its name was called Babel, because there Yahweh confused\u2026", "text": "The name \"Babel\" sounds like the word that means \"confused.\" Translators may want to add a footnote about this."}, {"ref": "confused the language of the whole earth", "text": "This could also be translated as \u201cmixed up the language of the whole earth.\u201d It means that Yahweh caused the people all over the earth to no longer speak the same language."}]}, {"id": "11-10", "tn": [{"ref": "", "text": "The rest of this chapter lists the 